Getting Started
This document explains how MyCase integrators can successfully utilize MyCase API's to integrate with our platform.

Obtaining Authorization
MyCase's API can only be accessed through OAuth 2.0 using the Authorization Code grant type. In order to access any of the API, your application must obtain authorization from the user.

For current MyCase customers, please reach out to MyCase support to receive necessary client credentials. https://www.mycase.com/support/

Authorization Code Grant Flow
Here's a breakdown of the process:

User Authorization: You will redirect the user to our authorization server using a URL that includes your client ID, and a redirect URI (explained below).

Redirect URI: The redirect URI is a critical component. It's the endpoint within your application where our server will redirect the user after they grant or deny access. You must specify a valid redirect URI when requesting client credentials. This redirect URI can only be set and updated by MyCase support.

Authorization Code: If the user grants access, our server redirects them back to your specified redirect URI. This redirection will include a unique authorization code within the URL parameters.

Token Exchange: Your application then uses this authorization code, along with your client credentials, to request an access token from our server.

API Access: The access token acts as a secure key that your application uses to make authenticated requests to our API.

Making API Requests
Once you recieve your client credentials from MyCase, follow the steps below to access the API:

1. Request an authorization code
To initiate the OAuth flow, send a GET request to the MyCase authorization server to obtain an authorization code.

Endpoint
GET https://auth.mycase.com/login_sessions/new

Required Query Parameters
client_id: Your OAuth Client ID provided by MyCase.
redirect_uri: The pre-registered redirect URI for your application.
response_type: Must be set to code.
Optional Query Parameter
state: An opaque value to maintain state between the request and callback. Use this to prevent cross-site request forgery and to pass any application-specific data.
Example Request
https://auth.mycase.com/login_sessions/new?client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID&redirect_uri=YOUR_REDIRECT_URI&response_type=code&state=YOUR_STATE_VALUE
If the user grants access to your application, MyCase will redirect the browser to the redirect url that you provided in the client credentials setup process with an authorization code.The URL will be formatted as ?code=.
If you receive a forbidden response, the authorizing user does not have sufficient privileges to authorize external applications. Please make sure that the authorizing user has the Manage your firm's preferences, billing, and payment options? permission set to Yes.
2. Exchange the authorization code for an access token
Send a POST request with the obtained authorization code along with your client credentials to request an access token at https://auth.mycase.com/tokens

POST Request Payload
Include the following parameters in your request body:

client_id: Required. The OAuth Client ID from your partner OAuth application.
client_secret: Required. The OAuth Client secret from your partner OAuth application.
code: Required. The authorization code obtained from the previous step.
grant_type: Required. Must be set to authorization_code.
redirect_uri: Required. The same redirect_uri used in the authorization flow.
Example POST request body:

{
  "client_id": "YOUR_CLIENT_ID",
  "client_secret": "YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET",
  "code": "AUTHORIZATION_CODE",
  "grant_type": "authorization_code",
  "redirect_uri": "YOUR_REDIRECT_URI"
}
Response
The tokens endpoint will return a JSON response with the following structure:

{
  "access_token": "TOKEN_VALUE",
  "token_type": "Bearer",
  "scope": "GRANTED_SCOPES",
  "refresh_token": "TOKEN_VALUE",
  "expires_in": 86400,
  "firm_uuid": "FIRM_UUID"
}
access_token: The token used to authenticate API requests.
token_type: Always "Bearer".
scope: A string containing all the granted scopes, separated by spaces.
refresh_token: Token used to obtain a new access token when the current one expires.
expires_in: The lifetime of the access token in seconds (86400 seconds = 24 hours).
firm_uuid: The unique identifier for the firm associated with this token.
Access tokens are valid for 24 hours by default. Refresh tokens are valid for 2 weeks.

3. Make an API request
All API endpoints require authentication using the HTTP bearer authentication scheme. Please include the access_token from the previous step in an authorization header

Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
Rate Limits
MyCase API implements rate limiting to ensure stable service for all integrators. The current limits are 25 requests per second per client.

4. Using Refresh token to acquire a new access token
If your access token is expired, you will receive a 401 Unauthorized response. You may get a new access token using the provided refresh_token in the following way:
Send a POST request with the refresh token along with your client credentials to request an refreshed access token at https://auth.mycase.com/tokens

POST Request Payload
Include the following parameters in your request body:

client_id: Required. The OAuth Client ID from your partner OAuth application.
client_secret: Required. The OAuth Client secret from your partner OAuth application.
refresh_token: Required. The authorization code obtained from the previous step.
grant_type: Required. Must be set to refresh_token.
Example POST request body:

{
  "client_id": "YOUR_CLIENT_ID",
  "client_secret": "YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET",
  "refresh_token": "TOKEN_VALUE",
  "grant_type": "refresh_token"
}
Response
The tokens endpoint will return a JSON response with the following structure:

{
  "access_token": "TOKEN_VALUE",
  "token_type": "Bearer",
  "scope": "GRANTED_SCOPES",
  "refresh_token": "TOKEN_VALUE",
  "expires_in": 86400
}
access_token: The token used to authenticate API requests.
token_type: Always "Bearer".
scope: A string containing all the granted scopes, separated by spaces.
refresh_token: Token used to obtain a new access token when the current one expires.
expires_in: The lifetime of the access token in seconds (86400 seconds = 24 hours).
Your requests may also fail if your application does not have the required scopes necessary to access specific API endpoints. Please contact us if you believe this is the case.